Exploratory Factor Analysis & Dimension Reduction

Jamie Reilly, Ph.D.

May 2024

EFA (Exploratory Factor Analysis)

What is affectvec?

We will be reading in a slightly streamlined version of Affectvec limited to 176 dimensions (spanning 80k or so English words). Here’s the structure of affectvec – It’s many English words (one word per row), each characterized on 176 different emotions. The problem is that many of these emotions are highly correlated (e.g., gloomy, melancholy, sadness). That produces multicollinearity problems. So you will want to reduce the dimensionality to an optimal number of orthogonalized latent factors.




Read in and prep data for EFA

Prep the dataframe:
1. Kill all non-numeric columns
2. Select not word, but save it! You need it to rebuld the dataframe later 

load(url("https://github.com/Reilly-ConceptsCognitionLab/reillylab_data/blob/main/affectvec_ordered.rda?raw=true"))
#load("lookup/affectvec_ordered.rda")
affvec_raw <- affectvec_ordered
affvec_justwords <- affvec_raw %>% select(word) # retain for building in later
affvec_justvals <- affvec_raw %>% select(-1) #eliminates 'word' column leaving only numeric vars

Determine # of factors

Determine the optimal number of factors from the correlation matrix retaining factors with an Eigenvalue >1. We need to change the uniqueness to converge (see factanal documentation).

affvec_scaled <- scale(affvec_justvals) #zscore all vals
affvec_cor <- cor(affvec_scaled) #cor matrix
affvec_eigen <- eigen(affvec_cor) 
print(affvec_eigen)

Run EFA

Save as new dataframe, export as RDA for preloading. We will use a 22 factor solution and extract the factor scores using Bartlett’s method.

#Run the factor analysis
affvec_EFA <- factanal(affvec_scaled, factors=22, rotation='varimax', scores='Bartlett', lower = 0.1)
affvec_facscores <- data.frame(affvec_EFA$scores)
#bind word column back into the dataframe
affvec_facscores <- cbind(affvec_justwords, affvec_facscores)
new2dat <- affvec_facscores

Inspect Factor Loadings

## Make dataframe of factor loadings
factor_loadings <- as.data.frame.matrix(affvec_EFA$loadings) %>% rownames_to_column(var = "affect")
## Generate new labels
factor_labels <- factor_loadings %>%pivot_longer(cols = -affect, 
               names_to = "factor",
               values_to = "loading") %>% 
  group_by(factor) %>%
  slice_max(loading, n = 1, with_ties = F) %>%   
  ungroup() %>%
  unite(label, factor, affect, sep = "_", remove = FALSE) 

## Re-label Factors in data frame with scores for each word 
affvec_facscores_labelled <- affvec_facscores %>% 
  rename_with(~ factor_labels$label[match(., factor_labels$factor)], .cols = factor_labels$factor)

#save as rda for quick load
affvec_22dim <- affvec_facscores_labelled
